---
description: UI form and title-bar consistency standards
alwaysApply: true
---

# UI Form Consistency (Angular)

- ALL components must use global style systems for formatting (size, spacing, font, colors).
- Use only these two global form style sets unless explicitly approved otherwise:
  - Standard page form styles
  - Title-bar form styles
- This applies to all form-adjacent UI elements:
  - Edit/input boxes
  - Checkboxes
  - Dropdown/select menus
  - Accordion/expansion sections
- Keep form sizing, spacing, and typography in global styles (`src/styles.scss`) using reusable classes.
- Avoid inline `style=""` in templates for form controls/title bars; use named classes instead.
- Treat parent page as source of truth for shared header fields (`Office`, `Property Code`, `Reservation`) and pass values down via inputs.
- Do not duplicate shared header fields inside child tabs unless explicitly requested.
- Prevent layout "jumping" across tabs: keep title-bar dimensions and action alignment stable when controls appear/disappear.
- Colors must be global and theme-driven (no local hardcoded component colors for standard UI patterns).
- `primary` and `accent` color usage must come from shared/global theme configuration.

# Save and Tab Behavior

- Use contextual Save from the parent title bar when tabs represent different save targets.
- Keep Save label simple (`Save`) unless user explicitly asks for contextual wording.
- Remove duplicate in-tab save buttons when parent contextual save is active.

# Component Member Style (Angular/TypeScript UI only)

- This visibility rule applies to `RentAll.Ui` only. It does NOT apply to `RentAll.Api` or `RentAll.Db`.
- For new variables and methods inside Angular components, do NOT add explicit `public`/`private` modifiers on **methods**. Remove `private` from methods when touching a file.
- Let class members use default visibility unless there is an explicit exception requested.
- Prefer Angular `inject()` for dependency injection over constructor parameter injection (`private readonly foo = inject(FooService)`).
- Do not add constructor-only boilerplate for DI; use a constructor only when it has real construction logic.
- When touching a file that still uses constructor DI, migrate that file's DI to `inject()` as part of the change when practical.
- Preferred class member order in components:
  1. `@Input` / `@Output` / `input()` / `output()`
  2. `inject()` dependencies
  3. Other fields/state (including fields whose initializers use injected services)
  4. Constructor only when it has real construction logic (after `super()` if extending)
  5. Lifecycle and methods (existing region rules below)
- Field initializers run top-to-bottom: never reference an `inject()` dependency above where it is declared.

# File Organization and Regions

- Use `//#region` / `//#endregion` blocks consistently across component files.
- First region should be the component's main functional region (example: `//#region Email-List`).
- Place lifecycle and primary action methods in that first region:
  - `ngOnInit`, `ngOnChanges`
  - core `get/add/update/save` methods
- Keep a dedicated `//#region Data Loading Methods` for external API/data-loading methods (examples: `loadProperties`, `loadOffices`, `loadReservations`).
- Keep a dedicated `//#region Build Form` for form construction and form-population logic:
  - `buildForm`, `populateForm`, `resetForm`
  - helper/support functions used for form building and form value mapping
- Keep `//#region Utility Methods` at the bottom of the component file.
  - Place `ngOnDestroy` and `back` methods there.

# RxJS Chain Formatting

- Prefer single-line RxJS chain starters before `subscribe`, e.g.:
  - `this.reservationService.getReservationList().pipe(take(1)).subscribe({`
  - `this.serviceCall().pipe(take(1), finalize(() => { ... })).subscribe({`
- Keep API service call expressions on one line regardless of length (do not wrap/chop the call chain unless required by syntax).
- Keep API call flows simple and direct; avoid unnecessary indirection around straightforward request/subscribe paths.
- Under `subscribe({ ... })`, keep the body focused on:
  - `next: ...`
  - `error: ...`
- Avoid `forkJoin` by default; prefer simpler sequential/targeted loading flows unless parallel aggregation is truly necessary.

# Comment Style

- Keep comments minimal and high-value only.
- Do NOT add routine/boilerplate comments around standard code (including `@Input`/`@Output`, simple assignments, obvious conditionals).
- Do NOT add change-tracking comments while editing (no "updated/removed/fixed" inline notes).
- Add comments only when logic is genuinely complex or non-obvious.

# Shared Data and Loading Pattern

- Global reference data (examples: states, offices, contacts) should be loaded once at app/session bootstrap and reused.
- Components should subscribe to shared/global data providers/stores rather than re-fetching duplicate reference data per component.
- Components should use the `utilityService` load-item gating pattern for loading state consistency:
  - `itemsToLoad$` as `BehaviorSubject<Set<string>>`
  - `isPageReady` boolean synced from set size (`items.size === 0`)
  - add/remove load items through utility helpers
- Use subscription lifecycle cleanup consistently (`destroy$` + `takeUntil(...)` and `ngOnDestroy` completion/unsubscribe).
- Prefer this standard component loading shell when applicable:
  - `globalOfficeSubscription?: Subscription`
  - `itemsToLoad$ = new BehaviorSubject<Set<string>>(new Set([...]))`
  - `isPageReady = false`
  - `destroy$ = new Subject<void>()`
  - In `ngOnInit`, subscribe: `this.itemsToLoad$.pipe(takeUntil(this.destroy$)).subscribe(items => { this.isPageReady = items.size === 0; ... })`
- Assume default property retrieval is org/user-scoped by API access control:
  - For users with access to multiple offices, default `getProperties` returns all properties they are allowed to access across those offices.
  - Office authorization filtering is enforced by the API.
  - UI should treat office selection primarily as client-side filtering of already-authorized data unless a specific server-side filtered endpoint is explicitly required.
- Avoid initial list "flash" from unfiltered-to-filtered data:
  - In list components that depend on global office scope, do not render final list content until office scope is resolved.
  - Gate loading with `itemsToLoad$` (for example, an `officeScope` load item) so users do not see a transient larger list first.
- Prefer separate loader methods over large multi-domain `forkJoin` loaders for component initialization.
  - Use dedicated methods like `loadOffices()`, `loadRegions()`, `loadAreas()`, `loadBuildings()`, etc.
  - Give each loader its own load-item key in `itemsToLoad$`.
  - Remove each key in that loader's `finalize(...)`.
  - Gate page render (`isPageReady`) until all required keys are cleared.
  - In templates: `@if (!isPageReady) { …spinner… }` / `@if (isPageReady) { …content… }`. Do **not** use `isLoading$` for this pattern.
  - `LoadingBarService.isLoading$` is the global HTTP progress bar only — unrelated to component page readiness.
  - Keep each loader focused and independently debuggable.

# Formatting Standard

- Components should use `formatterService` for formatting concerns (not inline/manual formatting logic).
- Keep mapping functionality in `mappingService` (avoid inline component-level mapping logic).
- Apply `formatterService` consistently for:
  - names/display strings
  - decimals/currency/number precision
  - boolean display text
  - phone/date-like presentation formatting

# Add/Edit Defaults

- In Add mode, use clear prompt defaults for required fields when requested (e.g., `Enter Code`) and enforce replacement via validation.
- For office selection in Add mode: if global office is specific, preselect it; if global office is "All Offices"/null, require explicit office selection.
- Keep owner choices office-consistent: owner dropdown options are filtered by selected office.

# Add/Edit CRUD Standard

Applies to list → form entity screens (Invoice, Receipt, Contact, Deposit, Reservation, Property, settings sub-forms, etc.). **Inline** (list row add) and **Dialog** flows are separate patterns and are not replaced by this standard.

## Entity id contract (all hosting modes)

Same semantics everywhere — **shell-embedded**, **route-hosted**, and **settings-embedded**:

- **Add:** `entityId === 'new'` (literal string). Do **not** use `null` for add.
- **Edit:** `entityId === <guid>` (or numeric id where the entity uses numbers).
- **Form and shell:** `isAddMode = entityId === 'new'`.
- **Route-hosted pages** use the same contract: route param `'new'` or guid. Route navigation is **hosting only**; it is not different add semantics.
- **Nothing open:** `selectedEntityId = null` (list visible only).

### Route-hosted vs shell-embedded

| Hosting | How add opens | Id source |
|---------|---------------|-----------|
| Shell-embedded | List emits / shell sets `'new'`, `@if` shows form | `@Input()` (`receiptId`, `id`, etc.) |
| Route-hosted | List navigates to `/…/new` | `ActivatedRoute` param `:id` |
| Settings (configuration) | List sets `entityId = 'new'`, `@if` shows form | `@Input()` from parent |

Both paths must pass or read `'new'` explicitly. A form component that supports standalone routes must resolve id from **route param first**, then `@Input` (see cost-codes / contact patterns).

### Forbidden add-mode detection

Do **not** infer add mode from any of the following:

- `!id`, `!entityId`, missing route param, or empty string → add
- `!id \|\| id === 'new'` or `id == null \|\| id === 'new'` for **`isAddMode`**
- `toLowerCase()`, `trim()`, or other normalization before comparing to `'new'`
- `paramMap.get('id') \|\| 'new'` or `id \|\| 'new'` as a default when param/input is missing
- `isAddMode = true` as a field default before id is resolved (default **`false`**)
- Duplicate save checks: `!invoiceId \|\| invoiceId === 'new' \|\| invoiceId === ''` — use **`this.isAddMode`**
- Redundant load guards: `isAddMode \|\| !receiptId \|\| receiptId === 'new'` — use **`if (this.isAddMode) return`** only

Missing or empty id when the form is shown means **wait, error, or return** — not add. Exception: embedded contact may coalesce empty `@Input` to `'new'` only when the shell always opens add with an explicit `'new'` selection.

### Dual-entity shell exception (maintenance only)

When **one shell** hosts **two entity types** on the same tab area (receipt vs work order), shell-level title-bar getters may use **`isReceiptAddMode`** / **`isWorkOrderAddMode`** derived from `selectedReceiptId === 'new'` and `selectedWorkOrderId === 'new'`. Form components still use plain **`isAddMode = entityId === 'new'`**. Do not introduce other entity-prefixed add-mode names elsewhere.

## List / shell vs form responsibilities

**List or shell owns:**

- `selectedEntityId: 'new' | string | null` when nothing is open (`null` = list visible only).
- Add → set `'new'`, show form (emit to shell or navigate to `/…/new`).
- Edit → set guid, show form.
- Back / close → hide form, clear selection (`selectedEntityId = null`).

**Form component owns:**

- Load/save API calls and validation.
- `buildForm`, `populateForm`, `resetForm` (see below).
- Deriving `isAddMode` from `entityId === 'new'` (shells: true when the active detail’s id is `'new'`).
- Save/create: `const isCreating = this.isAddMode` (or equivalent) — do not re-derive from id strings.

Pass the id into the form with a domain-named `@Input()` when one already exists (`receiptId`, `contactId`, `journalEntryId`, etc.). New work may use a consistent `entityId` input name when introducing new screens.

**GET/load guards** (e.g. `loadReceipt`, `loadJournalEntry`): early-return on `this.isAddMode`; do not treat null/empty id as add.

## Lifecycle: `@if` destroy (default for tabbed shells and settings)

For tabbed shells (accounting, maintenance, contacts, settings/configuration, emails) and settings sub-sections:

- List and form are **not** shown at the same time.
- Use `@if (showForm && selectedEntityId)` (or equivalent) to swap list ↔ form.
- **Close destroys** the form component. Do **not** keep the form mounted with `display: none`, `settings-section-hidden`, or `*DetailMounted` + CSS hide unless there is an approved, documented reason.
- Do **not** use `addAttemptToken` or similar remount hacks when `@if` destroy is in place.

**Re-open Add** (`'new'` twice without leaving the shell): increment a `*DetailInstance` counter when `entityId === 'new'` is selected again while add detail is already open, and wrap the form in `@for (instance of [detailInstance]; track instance)` so Angular destroys and recreates the form.

```html
@if (showContactForm) {
  <app-contact [id]="formContactId ?? 'new'" (closed)="onContactClosed($event)" />
} @else {
  <app-contact-list (openContact)="onOpenContact($event)" />
}
```

Settings (configuration) — prefer `@if (!(isEditing && entityId)) { list }` / `@if (isEditing && entityId) { form }`, not hiding the list with CSS while keeping it mounted.

## Form methods (`//#region Build Form`)

Every CRUD form component should define these three methods with consistent roles:

### `buildForm()`

- Create the `FormGroup`: controls, validators, empty `FormArray`s.
- Do **not** load API entity data here.
- Run once per component instance (typically from `ngOnInit`).

### `populateForm()`

- **Edit only:** map loaded entity state (`this.contact`, `this.receipt`, etc.) → form (`patchValue`, rebuild `FormArray`s).
- Call after GET succeeds.
- Guard: `if (!this.form || !this.entity) return`.
- May call `mappingService` / `formatterService` / `utilityService` for shared normalization and display formatting.
- Do **not** put `patchValue` logic in `mappingService`.

### `resetForm()`

- **Add / re-add:** return the form to add defaults and clear non-form state (upload previews, split lines, validation flags, cached entity).
- Call when `entityId` becomes `'new'` and the **same component instance** is reused (including after save-and-add-another on the same screen).
- When the shell **destroys** the form on close, a new instance runs `buildForm()` in `ngOnInit` instead; `resetForm()` may still exist for `ngOnChanges` or can delegate to `buildForm()` + add defaults.

**Call sequence:**

| Flow | Calls |
|------|--------|
| First open Add (new instance) | `buildForm()` → add defaults |
| Open Edit | `buildForm()` if needed → GET → `populateForm()` |
| Re-open Add (reused instance) | `resetForm()` |
| Re-open Add (`@if` destroy) | New instance → `ngOnInit` → `buildForm()` |

Do **not** introduce alternate names (`resetForAddMode`, `resetFormForNewEntry`, `initializeCreateForm`) in new or touched code; use `resetForm()`.

## Mapping vs populate

| Layer | Owner | Responsibility |
|-------|--------|----------------|
| **Map** | `mappingService` | API JSON ↔ `*Response` / `*Request`, list display rows, shared normalization |
| **Populate** | Component `populateForm()` | `*Response` → this screen's `FormGroup` (dates for pickers, formatted phone, form arrays) |

Mapping is reusable and form-agnostic. Populate is UI-specific and belongs on the component.

## Out of scope (different pattern)

- **Child tab guards** (lease, property-agreement, owner tabs): `!propertyId \|\| propertyId === 'new'` means “no persisted parent yet” — not `isAddMode` derivation.
- **Inline row add** and **dialog** CRUD — separate patterns.

## Migration (incremental)

When touching an entity form:

1. Add uses `'new'`, not `null`.
2. `isAddMode = entityId === 'new'` only; remove loose/null/trim/toLowerCase add detection.
3. Default `isAddMode = false`; set from id in `ngOnInit` / `ngOnChanges` / route param subscription.
4. Shell/settings use `@if` list ↔ form destroy (replace `display: none`, `settings-section-hidden`, `*DetailMounted` when practical).
5. Implement or rename to `buildForm` / `populateForm` / `resetForm`.
6. Save and load paths use `this.isAddMode`, not duplicated id string checks.
7. Standalone route forms: resolve `:id` from `ActivatedRoute` when `@Input` is absent.

New entities must follow this standard. Existing entities are migrated when changed or when fixing add/edit bugs.

# Practical Example

```html
<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<div class="header-title form-titlebar-fields-wrap">
  <mat-form-field class="titlebar-field-office"></mat-form-field>
  <mat-form-field class="titlebar-field-property-code"></mat-form-field>
</div>

<!-- ❌ BAD -->
<div style="display:flex; gap:8px;">
```
